[2] Cholera - Kenya (southwest counties)
Date: Sat 14 Mar 2015
Source: The Standard [edited]
http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/mobile/?articleID=2000154716&story_title=Alarm%20as%20cholera%20affects%20200%20pupils/thecounties/


Cholera is still a threat in Nyanza and neighboring regions. The disease, which broke out in Migori, Homa Bay and Kisii counties in January 2015, has so far claimed 30 lives and affected 1500 people. But even as county governments put on brave faces and report that the disease has been contained, The Standard on Saturday, 14 Mar 2015, has established that there are new cases reported in Migori. The revelation is causing fear among residents in the region who depend on cross-border trade as they mingle and eat in restaurants in the area. There are concerns that school children are prone to the disease given that some learn in crowded conditions.

New cases of cholera have been reported in Migori County where 11 people were diagnosed in Nyatike and 6 in Rongo within the last 3 days. This brings to light the fact that the number of people who have died from the disease could even be bigger than what has been reported. Though campaigns against cholera are now being intensified in schools, it has emerged that most victims who have been treated in local hospitals and health centres were children under the age of 15.

According to statistics seen by The Standard on Saturday 14 Mar 2015, 6 school-going children died from the epidemic while 200 were infected over the last 10 weeks.

Cholera 1st broke out in Rongo, Migori County in February 2015, when 723 people were diagnosed in the public health facilities and 6 succumbed. Speaking to The Standard on Saturday, the county health director Joel Gondi said efforts to attain zero cholera infections in the county have been thwarted by lack of clean water supplies to households. "A larger percentage of Migori residents have got no access to clean water and this has been the root cause of faster spread of cholera in the county," said Dr Gondi.

He said a big section of the population depends on water from River Migori for domestic use, yet it is polluted. The director appealed to the public to treat the water before use to stem cholera.

[Byline: Stanley Ongwae, James Omoro and Kassim Adinasi]

